|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{army|United States}}\n|serviceyears = 1963\u20131968\n}}\n'''Bobby Lee Rush''' (born November 23, 1946) is an American politician, civil rights leader and pastor. Rush is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|IL|1}}, serving in Congress for more than two decades; he was first elected in 1992 and took office in 1993. He has since won consecutive re-election. The district was located principally on the [[South Side (Chicago)|South Side]] of [[Chicago]], with a population from 2003 to early 2013 that was 65% [[African-American]], a higher proportion than any other [[congressional district]] in the nation. In 2011 the [[Illinois General Assembly]] redistricted this area following the 2010 census. While still [[minority-majority]], since early 2013 it is 51.3% African American, 9.8% Latino and 2% Asian. It re-elected Rush in 2016. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], Rush is the only politician to have defeated [[Barack Obama]] in an election, which he did in the [[Illinois's 1st congressional district election, 2000|2000 Democratic primary for Illinois' 1st congressional district]]. A civil rights activist during the 1960s, Rush became radicalized for a period and founded the Illinois chapter of the [[Black Panthers]].\n\n==Early life, education, and activism==\nRush was born on November 23, 1946 in [[Albany, Georgia]]. After his parents separated when Rush was 7 years old, his mother took him and his siblings to [[Chicago, Illinois]], joining the [[Great Migration (African American)|Great Migration]] of African Americans out of the South in the first part of the 20th century. In 1963 Rush dropped out of high school before graduating; he joined the [[U.S. Army]]. While stationed in Chicago in 1966, he joined the [[Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee]], which had helped obtain national civil rights legislation passed in 1964 and 1965. In 1968, he went [[AWOL]] from the Army and co-founded the Illinois chapter of the [[Black Panthers]]. He later finished his service, receiving an honorable discharge from the Army.\n\nThroughout the 1960s, Rush was involved in the [[civil rights movement]] and worked in civil disobedience campaigns in the [[southern United States]]. After co-founding the Illinois chapter of the [[Black Panther Party]] in 1968, he served as its defense minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/bobby-l.-rush--IL-H|title=Bobby L. Rush|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref> After Black Panther [[Fred Hampton]] was killed in a police raid, Rush said, \"We needed to arm ourselves\", and referred to the police as \"pigs\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasentinel.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1144:bobby-rush&catid=79&Itemid=169|title=Bobby Rush \u2013 LA Sentinel|work=[[Los Angeles Sentinel]]|date=January 5, 2012|accessdate=December 20, 2012|author=Yussuf J. Simmonds}}</ref> Earlier that same year Rush had discussed the philosophy of his membership in the Black Panthers saying, \"Black people have been on the defensive for all these years. The trend now is not to wait to be attacked. We advocate offensive violence against the power structure.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=A Black Panther on Little Cat Feet; Bobby Rush Drops the Clenched Fist|author=Kevin Klose|publisher=Washington Post|date=August 11, 1984}}</ref> After Hampton's death, Rush became acting chairman of the Illinois Black Panther Party.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Koziol |first1=Ronald|title=Bobby Rush Acting Chief of Panthers: Succeeds Slain Leader Hampton |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1969/12/11/page/3/article/bobby-rush-acting-chief-of-panthers|accessdate=July 28, 2017 |publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=December 11, 1969}}</ref>\n\nRush worked on several non-violent projects that built support for the Black Panthers in African-American communities, such as coordinating a medical clinic which offered [[sickle-cell anemia]] testing on an unprecedented scale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/elections/candidate/494|title=''Washington Times'' report on Rush's sickle-cell anemia program |work=Washington Times|accessdate=November 23, 2016}}</ref> Rush's own apartment was raided in December 1969, where police discovered an unregistered pistol, rifle, shotgun, pistol ammunition, training manuals on explosives, booby traps, an assortment of communist literature, and a small amount of [[marijuana]].<ref>{{cite web|title=CBS Evening News|author=Bill Matney|publisher=CBS |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WTUFIRd32FM|accessdate=November 23, 2016}}</ref> Rush was imprisoned for six months in 1972 on a weapons charge, after carrying a pistol into a police station. In 1974, he left the Panthers, who were already in decline. ''\"We started glorifying thuggery and drugs\"'', he told ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine. Rush, a deeply religious born-again [[Christian]], said, ''\"I don't repudiate any of my involvement in the Panther party\u2014it was part of my maturing.\"''<ref>{{cite book |title=Almanac of American Politics|publisher=National Journal Group|accessdate=November 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Formal education==\nIn 1973, Rush earned his [[Bachelor of General Studies]] with honors from [[Roosevelt University]], and a [[Master's degree]] in [[political science]] from [[University of Illinois at Chicago]] in 1974. He completed a degree in [[theology|theological studies]] at [[McCormick Theological Seminary]] in 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=r000515 |title=RUSH, Bobby L. - Biographical Information |website=Bioguide.congress.gov |accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref> On May 13, 2017 Rush received an Honorary Doctorate of Humanities, honoris causa, from the Illinois Institute of Technology (IIT) for his outstanding contributions to Chicago.\n\n==Politics==\n===Chicago politics===\nIn 1974, Rush ran for a seat on the [[Chicago City Council]], the first of several black militants to seek political office, and was defeated. Rush's allies in the black-power movement abandoned the Democrats in the wake of the political turmoil that followed Washington's sudden death in 1987 and formed their own political party, naming it after the late mayor. Rush infuriated Harold Washington Party leaders by spurning their candidates for local offices and, on occasion, backing white Democrats instead. Rush worked with the regular Democrats and was rewarded with the deputy chairmanship of the state party.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Secter|first1=Bob |title=Column One : From Scout to Panther to Politico : Bobby Rush, onetime head of the Illinois Black Panthers, is likely to be the first '60s radical leader to end up in Congress. As an Establishment figure, his loyalties are questioned. |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-04-17/news/mn-702_1_black-panther|accessdate=July 28, 2017|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=April 17, 1992}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Chicago mayoral election, 1999|1999]], Rush ran for [[Mayor of Chicago]], but lost in the Democratic primary to incumbent [[Richard M. Daley]], an ethnic [[Irish American]] whose father had long controlled the city as mayor.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ryan |last=Lizza|url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2008/07/21/080721fa_fact_lizza|title=Making It: How Chicago Shaped Obama|work=The New Yorker|date=July 21, 2008}}</ref> He remained active in city and regional politics.\n\nIn 2013, Rush criticized a proposal by former Republican Senator [[Mark Kirk]] who suggested that 18,000 members of the Chicago gang \"Gangster Disciples\" be arrested. Rush called Kirk's approach \"headline grabbing\", and said it was an \"upper-middle-class, elitist white boy solution to a problem he knows nothing about\". A spokesman for Kirk said the Congressman had dealt with the issues for decades.<ref>[http://www.jdjournal.com/2013/05/30/bobby-rush-condemns-mark-kirks-mass-gang-arrest-plan-as-elitist-white-boy-solution/ June, Daniel, \"Bobby Rush Condemns Mark Kirk's Mass Gang Arrest Plan as 'Elitist White Boy Solution'\"], jdjournal.com, May 30, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Rush endorsed Mayor [[Rahm Emanuel]] in Emanuel's run-off reelection campaign against [[Jesus \"Chuy\" Garcia]].<ref>Bosman, Julie, [http://mobile.nytimes.com/2015/04/04/us/candidate-for-chicago-mayor-struggles-to-unite-latinos-and-blacks.html \"Struggles to Unite Latinos and Blacks\"], ''New York Times'', April 3, 2015.</ref>\n\n===Endorsement of Obama for President===\nThough a very close friend to former President [[Bill Clinton]] and his wife, politician [[Hillary Clinton]], Rush announced early on in the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2008|2008 Democratic primaries]] that he would support Barack Obama.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/politics/231872,CST-NWS-obama27.article|title=Clinton pal Bobby Rush: I'm supporting Obama |date=January 27, 2008|accessdate=January 2, 2009|publisher=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Fornek, Scott}}</ref> After Obama won the Presidency and vacated his Senate seat, Rush proposed that an African American should be appointed to fill that seat.<ref name=cpr>{{cite news |title=Rush Petitions For African-American To Replace Obama in the Senate|first=Tasha|last=Flournoy|work=Chicago Public Radio |date=December 2, 2008|url=http://www.wbez.org/Content.aspx?audioID=30530}}</ref> During a press conference, Rush said, \"With the resignation of President-elect Obama, we now have no African-Americans in the [[United States Senate]], and we believe it will be a national disgrace to not have this seat filled by one of the many capable African-American Illinois politicians.\"<ref name=bd>{{cite news|title=Cong. Bobby Rush urges governor to choose Black Senate replacement|work=Chicago Defender|date=December 3, 2008 |url=http://www.chicagodefender.com/article-2611-cong-bobby-rush-urge.html}}</ref> Rush said he did not support any particular person, and he was not interested in the seat.<ref name=cpr/><ref name=bd/> On December 30, 2008, Governor [[Rod Blagojevich]] announced his appointment of [[Roland Burris]], the former [[Attorney General of Illinois]]; Rush was present at the press conference and spoke in support of Burris.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/12/30/illinois.senate/index.html|title=Blagojevich names Obama successor despite warnings|publisher=CNN.com|date=December 30, 2008|accessdate=December 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\n{{See also|Illinois' 1st congressional district|Illinois' 1st congressional district election, 2000}}\nAfter redistricting in 1992, Rush decided to run in the newly redrawn [[Illinois' 1st congressional district]], which included much of the South Side of Chicago. The district had a high proportion of African-American residents. Rush defeated incumbent U.S. Congressman [[Charles A. Hayes|Charles Hayes]] and six other candidates in the Democratic [[Primary election|primary]] election in 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=207822|title=IL \u2013 District 01 \u2013 D Primary Race|date=March 17, 1992|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref> He won the general election with 83% of the vote.<ref name=\"IL DIstrict 1 Race \u2013 Nov 03, 1992\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=27837|title=IL DIstrict 1 Race|date=November 3, 1992|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref> In the 2000 Democratic primary for the Illinois' 1st congressional district, Rush was challenged by young [[Illinois Senate|Illinois State Senator]] [[Barack Obama]].<ref>[http://www.fec.gov/pubrec/fe2000/ilh.htm U.S. House of Representatives Election Results 2000]</ref> During the primary, Rush said, \"Barack Obama went to [[Harvard]] and became an educated fool. Barack is a person who read about the civil rights protests and thinks he knows all about it.\"<ref name=fool>{{cite news|last=Remnick|first=David|work=New Yorker|title=The Joshua Generation: Race and the Campaign of Barack Obama|date=November 17, 2008|url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2008/11/17/081117fa_fact_remnick?currentPage=all}}</ref>\n\nRush claimed Obama was insufficiently rooted in Chicago's black neighborhoods to represent constituents' concerns.<ref name=Kleine20000317>{{cite news|author=Kleine, Ted|newspaper=Chicago Reader|date=March 17, 2000|accessdate=July 26, 2008 |url=http://www.chicagoreader.com/obama/000317|title=Is Bobby Rush in trouble?}}</ref> For his part, Obama said Rush was a part of \"a politics that is rooted in the past\" and said he could build bridges with whites to get things done. But while Obama did well in his own [[Hyde Park, Chicago|Hyde Park]] [[Base (politics)|base]], he did not get enough support from the surrounding black neighborhoods.<ref name=jbcdnyt>{{cite news|last=Becker|first=Jo|author2=Christopher Drew|date=May 11, 2008|title=Pragmatic Politics, Forged on the South Side|newspaper=The New York Times|page=A1|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/11/us/politics/11chicago.html|accessdate=July 28, 2008}}</ref> Starting with 10% name recognition, Obama eventually gained 30% of the vote, losing by a more than 2-to-1 margin despite winning among white voters. Rush won 61% of the votes overall.<ref>Federal Election Commission, [http://www.fec.gov/pubrec/fe2000/ilh.htm 2000 U.S. House of Representatives Results]</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Gonyea, Don |date=September 19, 2007|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=14502364|title=Obama's loss may have aided White House bid|work=Morning Edition|publisher=NPR|accessdate=April 22, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Janny|last=Scott|title=A streetwise veteran schooled young Obama|date=September 9, 2007|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/09/us/politics/09obama.html |newspaper=The New York Times|page=A1|accessdate=April 20, 2008}}</ref><ref name=McClelland20070212>{{cite news|first=Edward |last=McClelland|title=How Obama learned to be a natural|date=February 12, 2007 |url=http://www.salon.com/news/feature/2007/02/12/obama_natural|publisher=Salon.com|accessdate=April 20, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=141037|title=IL District 1 \u2013 D Primary Race|date=March 21, 2000|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref> Rush won the general election for the district with 88% of the vote.<ref name=\"IL District 1 Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2000\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=448|title=IL District 1 Race |date=November 7, 2000|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nRush has been considered a loyal Democrat during his tenure; in the 110th Congress, he voted with his party 97.8% of the time.<ref name=\"Bobby Rush WRG\">{{cite news|title=Who Runs Gov Bobby Rush Profile|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/bobby-lee-rush-d-ill/gIQAPjFgAP_topic.html|work=Who Runs Gov|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=June 28, 2012|first=Hayley|last=Tsukayama}}</ref> Rush is a member of the [[Congressional Black Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership |url=https://cbc.house.gov/membership/ |publisher=Congressional Black Caucus|accessdate=March 7, 2018}}</ref> and the [[House Baltic Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Members|url=http://housebalticcaucus.webs.com/members|publisher=House Baltic Caucus|accessdate=February 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Issues===\n;Fiscal\nRush initiated the Chicago Partnership for the Earned Income Tax Credit, an ongoing program designed to help low-income [[Working class|working]] Chicago resident to receive the [[Earned Income Tax Credit]], a [[Taxation in the United States|federal]] [[Income tax in the United States|income tax]] [[Tax credit|credits]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rush|first1=Bobby|title=Voice of the People (Letter): Rep. Rush's Record Speaks For Itself|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-10-18/news/9510180341_1_empowerment-zones-constituents-1st-congressional-district|accessdate=March 25, 2017|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=October 18, 1995}}</ref>\n\n;Healthcare\nRush sponsored the Nursing Relief for Disadvantaged Areas Act passed in 1999. The law temporarily addressed the nursing shortage by providing non-immigrant visas for qualified foreign nurses in the [[Englewood, Chicago|Englewood]] neighborhood of Chicago and was reauthorized in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R.441|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/106th-congress/house-bill/441 |website=Congress.gov|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> Rush sponsored the Melanie Blocker-Stokes Postpartum Depression Research and Care Act, named for Melanie Blocker-Stokes, a Chicago native who jumped to her death from a 12th-story window due to [[postpartum depression]]. The bill would provide for research on postpartum depression and psychosis and services for individuals suffering from these disorders.<ref>{{cite web|title= H.R.20|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/110th-congress/house-bill/20 |website=Congress.gov |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> The [[Children's Health Act]], passed in 2000, incorporated Rush's Urban Asthma Reduction Act of 1999, amending the Preventive Health and Health Services Block Grant program and including an integrated approach to [[asthma]] management.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Barber|first1=John T.|title=The Black Digital Elite: African American Leaders of the Information Revolution|date=2006|publisher=Praeger|isbn=0-275-98504-0|page=50}}</ref>\n\n;Energy\nRush was very outspoken against the GOP's \"No More Solyndras\" Bill, which would override a loan guarantee by the Energy Department to encourage research and development. The Energy Department guaranteed a federal loan contract with the Solyndras company to help with R&D.<ref>{{cite news|title=GOP on House panel OKs 'no more Solyndras' bill|author=Andrew Restuccia |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0712/78987.html|newspaper=Politico|date=July 25, 2012|accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref> He said the \"No More Solyndras Bill\" would be better named as the \"No More Innovation Bill\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Rep. Bobby Rush: GOP's \"No More Solyndras Bill\" should be called \"No More Innovation Bill\"|url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/rep.-bobby-rush-gops-no-more-solyndras-bill-should-be-called-no-more-innovation-bill/article/2503173#.UC2l9allQcY|newspaper= Washington Examiner |date=July 25, 2012|accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Firearms\nRush introduced the \"Blair Holt's Firearm Licensing and Record of Sale Act of 2009\" on January 6, 2009. The bill would require all owners of handguns and semiautomatic firearms to register for a federal firearms license. All sales of the subject firearms would have to go through a licensed dealer. It would also make it a criminal act not to register as an owner of a firearm.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h111-45|title=H.R. 45: Blair Holt's Firearm Licensing and Record of Sale Act of 2009|publisher=GovTrack.us|accessdate=August 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n;Darfur genocide\nOn July 15, 2004, Rush became the second sitting [[member of Congress]], following [[Charles B. Rangel|Charles Rangel]] and preceding [[Joe Hoeffel]], to be arrested for [[trespassing]] while protesting the [[War in Darfur|genocide in Darfur]] and other violations of [[human rights in Sudan]] in front of the [[Diplomatic missions of Sudan#North America|Sudanese Embassy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. lawmaker arrested at Sudanese embassy in Washington|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Sudan Tribune|date=July 15, 2004 |url=http://www.sudantribune.com/spip.php?article4001}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.house.gov/list/press/il01_rush/pr_040715arrestedatsudaneseembassy.html|title=U.S. Rep. Bobby Rush Arrested at Sudanese Embassy|publisher=Office of Congressman Bobby Rush|date=July 15, 2004}}</ref>\n\n;Armed forces\nOn February 13, 2007, Rush opposed [[United States President|President]] [[George W. Bush]]'s proposed 20,000-serviceman troop surge in Iraq. He said the presence of the troops in Iraq was the greatest catalyst of violence in Iraq, and advocated a political resolution of the situation. Rush stated that the troop surge would only serve to make the Iraqi situation more volatile.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getpage.cgi?dbname=2007_record&page=H1532&position=all|title=Retrieve Pages |publisher=Frwebgate.access.gpo.gov|accessdate=August 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n;Trayvon Martin\nOn March 28, 2012, Rush addressed the House while wearing a [[hoodie]] in honor of [[Trayvon Martin]], a teenager who was shot in Florida by a local resident. He spoke against [[racial profiling]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/17542979|work=BBC News|title=Congressman Bobby Rush wears hoodie on House floor|date=March 28, 2012}}</ref> As the House forbids its members from wearing headgear, Rush was called out of order and escorted from the chamber.<ref>{{cite news|last=Madison|first=Lucy|title=Dem Rep. Bobby Rush escorted from House floor for wearing hoodie in honor of Trayvon Martin|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-57405846-503544/dem-rep-bobby-rush-escorted-from-house-floor-for-wearing-hoodie-in-honor-of-trayvon-martin/|newspaper=CBS News |date=March 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Israel [[Anti-Boycott]] Act\nOn September 5, 2017, Rush became the sole co-sponsor of H.R. 1697 to withdraw his support of the bill, which would require the United States to side with Israel against a United Nations resolution sanctioning Israel for human rights abuses.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/1697/cosponsors#|title=Cosponsors - H.R.1697 - 115th Congress (2017-2018): Israel Anti-Boycott Act|last=Peter|first=Roskam,|date=June 28, 2018|website=www.congress.gov|language=en|access-date=August 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nIn the [[115th United States Congress]] (January 3, 2017, to January 3, 2019):\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]]'''\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Communications and Technology|Subcommittee on Communications and Technology]]\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Energy and Power|Subcommittee on Energy]] (Ranking Member)\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Afterschool Caucuses]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|url=http://www.afterschoolalliance.org/policyCongressionalCaucuses.cfm |publisher=Afterschool Alliance|accessdate=April 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Missed votes===\nRush's career average missed vote percentage is 15.7, which is high compared to the median missed vote percentage of 2.2 for members of the U.S. House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Boyce|first1=Tessa|title=Members of Congress Who Miss the Most Votes |url=http://members-of-congress.insidegov.com/stories/10197/members-congress-miss-votes#Intro|accessdate=March 22, 2017 |publisher=InsideGov.com|date=January 25, 2016}}</ref> However, most of his absences were between 2014 and 2016 and he asserts that serious health problems kept him from D.C. In the first session of the 114th session of Congress (January 2015 to December 2015), Rush missed 15.6% of the votes and ranked #12 in most missed votes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Boyce|first1=Tessa|title=Members of Congress Who Miss the Most Votes: #12: Bobby Rush|url=http://members-of-congress.insidegov.com/stories/10197/members-congress-miss-votes#14-Bobby-Rush|accessdate=March 22, 2017|issue=January 25, 2016|publisher=InsideGov.com}}</ref> Rush had the distinction of missing more votes than any other member of the House of Representatives between 2007 and 2015: out of 6,906 votes, Rush missed 1,549 or 22.4%. Health issues for Rush and his wife were his main explanations for his high number of missed votes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Willis|first1=Derek |title=Personal Explanations: When Members of Congress Miss Votes, and Why |url=https://projects.propublica.org/explanations/|accessdate=February 28, 2017|publisher=ProPublica|date=November 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Connolly|first1=Colleen|title=Study: Illinois Reps. Bobby Rush, Luis Gutierrez Miss Most Votes in House |url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/ward-room/Rep-Bobby-Rush-Luis-Gutierrez-Miss-Most-House-Votes-346035222.html|accessdate=February 28, 2017|publisher=NBC Chicago|date=November 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Ethics concerns===\nThe [[Office of Congressional Ethics]] referred a matter involving Rush to the [[House Ethics Committee]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Skiba|first1=Katherine|title=House Ethics Committee continuing Rush investigation|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/chi-house-ethics-investigation-rush-20140725-story.html |accessdate=February 26, 2017|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=July 25, 2014}}</ref> The Office of Congressional Ethics report found he did not pay about $365,000 in rent for longtime use of an office to conduct politics.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Skiba|first1=Katherine |title=Report spells out alleged ethics misconduct by Rep. Rush|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/chi-bobby-rush-20141110-story.html|accessdate=February 26, 2017|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=November 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hess|first1=Hannah|title=In Bobby Rush Case, Was the Rent Too Darn Low?|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/ethics-committee-will-continue-review-of-bobby-rush|accessdate=March 24, 2017|publisher=RollCall.com|date=November 10, 2014}}</ref>\nRush has paid family members for years in questionable practices. Rush had a family member who for years worked for his church but was paid by a campaign supporter and friend.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Neubauer|first1=Chuck|title=THE WATCHDOGS: Campaign donor paid salary of Rep. Bobby Rush's niece|url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/news/the-watchdogs-campaign-donor-paid-salary-of-rep-bobby-rushs-niece/ |accessdate=February 25, 2017|publisher=Chicago Sun-Times|date=September 12, 2015}}</ref> The [[Federal Election Commission]] questioned Rush's campaign over a campaign-finance report that showed thousands of dollars spent on vague categories such as \"campaign visibility\" and \"services rendered.\" His campaign paid his wife, Carolyn, $50,000 in 2015 for consulting, and his brother, Marlon Rush of Lansing, $13,000 in 2016 for two months' work as campaign manager, according to FEC reports.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Skiba |first1=Katherine|title=Federal Election Commission questions Rep. Bobby Rush's campaign spending |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-bobby-rush-spending-reports-questioned-0518-20160517-story.html|accessdate=February 25, 2017 |publisher=Chicago Tribune}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Schoffstall|first1=Joe|title=Rep. Bobby Rush Paid Wife $550K From Campaign Funds, Kicked $190K to Church He Founded|url=http://freebeacon.com/politics/rep-bobby-rush-paid-wife-550k-campaign-funds-kicked-190k-church-founded/|accessdate=February 25, 2017|publisher=The Washington Free Beacon|date=July 8, 2016}}</ref> Oxford Media Group Inc., an Oak Brook company owned by multimillionaire businessman Joseph Stroud, paid the Commonwealth Edison bill \u2014 which was well past due, totaling $17,900 for Rush's Beloved Community Christian Church in 2010. Rush had personally been named in a ComEd lawsuit over the church's previous unpaid bills. Stroud was trying to break into the wireless phone industry dominated by Verizon and AT&T, and Rush was pushing for federal tax incentives that would give one of Stroud's other companies a leg up as a minority-owned business. A nonprofit Rush started got $1 million from the charitable arm of what's now AT&T for what turned out to be a failed effort to create a \"technology center\" in Englewood. At the time, the telecom giant was seeking support for legislation in a House committee on which Rush was a key member.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Neubauer|first1=Chuck|title=Exec seeking federal help paid $17,900 bill for Rep. Bobby Rush's church|url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/politics/exec-seeking-federal-help-paid-17900-bill-for-rep-bobby-rushs-church/ |accessdate=March 24, 2017|publisher=Chicago Sun-Times|date=June 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Electoral history===\n{{s-start}}\n|-\n| colspan=10 |<center>'''[[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House]], [[Illinois' 1st congressional district|1st District of Illinois]]''' (General Election)<ref name=\"IL DIstrict 1 Race \u2013 Nov 03, 1992\"/><ref name=\"IL District 1 Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2000\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=1067|title=IL District 1 Race \u2013 Nov 05, 2002|publisher=Our Campaigns |accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=206844 |title=IL \u2013 District 01 Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2006|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=387957|title=IL \u2013 District 01 Race \u2013 Nov 04, 2008|publisher=Our Campaigns |accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=489024|title=IL \u2013 District 01 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 2010|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://elections.huffingtonpost.com/2012/results/illinois#house-races 2012 election results], huffingtonpost.com; accessed February 23, 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=General Election - 11/4/2014 1ST Congress |url=http://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionInformation/VoteTotalsList.aspx?ElectionType=OcxMFeCn%2f2s%3d&ElectionID=vTUhLdn7S%2bI%3d&SearchType=qSfAwUdk1qOFOZFs8GbBdddK0yLOKECmUkSdD0Lok1c%3d&OfficeID=H%2fbbj%2fiRHzYxvrbY0qXb6g%3d%3d&QueryType=qSfAwUdk1qOEjNYZC1%2bXwQ%3d%3d&|website=Illinois State Board of Elections|accessdate=March 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Election Results General Election - 11/8/2016|url=http://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionResults.aspx?ID=vlS7uG8NT%2f0%3d|website=Illinois State Board of Elections|accessdate=March 26, 2017}}</ref></center>\n|-\n!Year\n!Winning candidate\n!Party\n!Pct\n!Opponent\n!Party\n!Pct\n!Opponent\n!Party\n!Pct\n|-\n|[[United States House elections, 1992|1992]]\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |'''Bobby Rush'''\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |82%\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |Jay Walker\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |17%\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House elections, 1994|1994]]\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |'''Bobby Rush (inc.)'''\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Democratic\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |75%\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |[[William J. Kelly]]\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |Republican\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |24%\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House elections, 1996|1996]]\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |'''Bobby Rush (inc.)'''\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Democratic\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |85%\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |Noel Naughton\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |Republican\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |12%\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |Tim M. Griffin\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |[[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |1%\n|-\n|[[United States House elections, 1998|1998]]\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |'''Bobby Rush (inc.)'''\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Democratic\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |87%\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |Marlene W. Ahimaz\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |Republican\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |10%\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |Maggie Kohls\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |Libertarian\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |2%\n|-\n|[[United Sta