} |Republican\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |15%\n|{{party shading/Green}} |Jeff Adams\n|{{party shading/Green}} |[[Green Party (United States)|Green]]\n|{{party shading/Green}} |3%\n|-\n|[[United States House elections, 2012|2012]]\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |'''Bobby Rush (inc.)'''\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Democratic\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |73%\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |Donald Peloquin\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |Republican\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |26%\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House elections, 2014|2014]]\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |'''Bobby Rush (inc.)'''\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Democratic\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |73%\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |Jimmy Tillman\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |Republican\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |27%\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House elections, 2016|2016]]\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |'''Bobby Rush (inc.)'''\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Democratic\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |74%\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |August Deuser\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |Republican\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |26%\n|\n|\n|\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Beloved Community Christian Church==\nRush is pastor of the Beloved Community Christian Church in the Englewood neighborhood of Chicago. Leaders of other Englewood non-profit organizations complained that the church's programs\u2014a community development corporation Rebirth of Englewood, a public health center, and a group serving teens convicted of crimes\u2014received an inordinate amount of government aid and weighed heavily on their own efforts for renewal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Olivo|first1=Antonio|title=Pastor Rush stirs hope, skeptics in Englewood: Bold vision for area's rebirth draws questions|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2006-01-01/news/0601010362_1_neighborhood-build-revitalization/3 |accessdate=March 2, 2017|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=January 1, 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Unpaid taxes and wage garnishment==\nIn 2013, Rush and his wife, the Beloved Community Christian Church of which Rush is pastor, and another nonprofit organization operating out of the church had tax delinquencies that added up to $195,000, and the pattern of tax delinquency was a decade old. Unpaid taxes included property taxes, income taxes, and employee withholding taxes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Neubauer|first1=Chuck |title=No Rush to Payment|url=http://www.bettergov.org/news/no-rush-to-payment|accessdate=March 1, 2017|publisher=Better Government Association|date=December 14, 2013}}</ref> New City Bank sued Rush and his wife for $500,000, claiming they failed to pay their property taxes in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Roe|first1=David|title=Bank Sues Cong. Rush, Claims Unpaid Property Tax |url=http://chicago.cbslocal.com/2010/11/04/bank-sues-cong-rush-claims-unpaid-property-tax/|accessdate=March 1, 2017|publisher=WBBM CBS Chicago|date=November 4, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Yue|first1=Lorene|title=Rep. Bobby Rush sued by bank over home mortgages |url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20101104/NEWS02/101109915/rep-bobby-rush-sued-by-bank-over-home-mortgages|accessdate=March 1, 2017|publisher=Crain's Chicago Business|date=November 4, 2010}}</ref> In 1994, Rush owed the Internal Revenue Service $55,000 in federal income taxes, according to Cook County records.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gibson|first1=Ray|title=Rush Owes Back Taxes To The IRS |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-06-17/news/9406170119_1_tax-lien-filed-irs|accessdate=March 1, 2017|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=June 17, 1994}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 2018, 15 percent of Rush's congressional salary is being garnished to repay more than $1 million he owes on a delinquent loan for the now-closed church he founded in Chicago. Cook County Circuit Judge Alexander White ordered Rush to repay the $550,000 loan that New City Bank granted him and seven other co-signers in 2005. With the money, Rush bought the former Our Redeemer Lutheran Church in Chicago's Englewood neighborhood and restyled it as the Beloved Community Church of God in Christ.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Connolly |first1=Griffin |title=Rep. Bobby Rush Faces Wage Garnishment on $1 Million Debt |url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/rep-bobby-rush-faces-wage-garnishment-1-million-debt |accessdate=20 October 2018 |publisher=Roll Call |date=Mar 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRush has been married three times.<ref name=\"McRobertsCohen1999\">{{cite news |last1=McRoberts |first1=Flynn |last2=Cohen |first2=Laurie |date=February 16, 1999 |title=Challenger Sees Self as Man of the People |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1999-02-16-9902160300-story.html |dead-url=no |work=Chicago Tribune |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928024000/https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1999-02-16-9902160300-story.html |archive-date=September 28, 2018 |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Ihejirika2018\">{{cite news |last=Ihejirika |first=Maudlyne |date=July 5, 2018 |title=Congressman Bobby Rush remarries |url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/news/bobby-rush-remarried-paulette-holloway-congressman/ |dead-url=no |work=Chicago Sun-Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712075247/https://chicago.suntimes.com/news/bobby-rush-remarried-paulette-holloway-congressman/ |archive-date=July 12, 2018 |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> His first marriage was to Sandra Milan, from when he was 19 years old until their divorce in 1973.<ref name=\"McRobertsCohen1999\"/><ref name=\"NNDB\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nndb.com/people/297/000040177/ |title=Bobby Rush |year=2014 |website=NNDB |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813112204/http://www.nndb.com/people/297/000040177/ |archive-date=August 13, 2018 |dead-url=no |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> They had two children together.<ref name=\"McRobertsCohen1999\"/> He was later married to community organizer, precinct captain and political strategist Carolyn Thomas from 1980 or 1981 until her death from [[congestive heart failure]] on March 13, 2017.<ref name=\"NNDB\"/><ref name=\"Skiba2017\">{{cite news |last=Skiba |first=Katherine |date=March 13, 2017 |title=Carolyn Rush, wife of U.S. Rep. Bobby Rush, dies at 67 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-bobby-rush-wife-dead-met-0313-20170313-story.html |dead-url=no |work=Chicago Tribune |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117110257/https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-bobby-rush-wife-dead-met-0313-20170313-story.html |archive-date=November 13, 2017 |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Rush2017\">{{cite web |url=https://rush.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rush-announces-the-passing-of-his-wife-carolyn-rush-68 |title=Rush Announces the Passing of His Wife Carolyn Rush, 67 |date=March 13, 2017 |website=United States House of Representatives: Congressman Bobby L. Rush |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922040018/https://rush.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rush-announces-the-passing-of-his-wife-carolyn-rush-68 |archive-date=September 22, 2018 |dead-url=no |accessdate=September 28, 2018}}</ref> They had a [[blended family]] with seven surviving children at the time of her death.<ref name=\"Skiba2017\"/> On June 30, 2018 he married his third wife, minister and author Paulette Holloway.<ref name=\"Ihejirika2018\"/>\n\nRush had a son, Huey Rich, in November 1969, who was murdered on the South Side of Chicago at the age of 29.<ref name=\"McCormick1999\">{{cite news |last=McCormick |first=John |date=November 28, 1999 |title=A Father's Anguished Journey |url=https://www.newsweek.com/fathers-anguished-journey-164318 |dead-url=yes |work=Newsweek |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215184923/https://www.newsweek.com/fathers-anguished-journey-164318 |archive-date=January 25, 2013 |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Loven1999\">{{cite news |last=Loven |first=Jennifer |date=December 19, 1999 |title=Son's Slaying Transforms Congressman's Priorities |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/dec/19/news/mn-45448 |dead-url=no |work=Los Angeles Times |agency=Associated Press |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928040119/http://articles.latimes.com/1999/dec/19/news/mn-45448 |archive-date=September 28, 2018 |access-date=September 28, 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"WilsonHill1999\">{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Terry |last2=Hill |first2=James |date=October 26, 1999 |title=Suspect Charged in Slaying of Rush\u2019s Son |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1999-10-26-9910260092-story.html |dead-url=no |work=Chicago Tribune |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215184923/https://www.newsweek.com/fathers-anguished-journey-164318 |archive-date=February 15, 2018 |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> He was named after Black Panther co-founder [[Huey P. Newton]]. Rich's mother was Saundra Rich, who Rush never married.<ref name=\"Loven1999\"/> On October 18, 1999, Rich was approached outside his apartment building by Leo Foster and Darcell Prince, who falsely claimed to be police officers.<ref name=\"Madhani2002\">{{cite news |last=Madhani |first=Aamer |date=March 15, 2002 |title=2 Found Guilty of Murdering Rush\u2019s Son |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/g00/news/ct-xpm-2002-03-15-0203150197-story.html |dead-url=no |work=Chicago Tribune |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928070133/https://www.chicagotribune.com/g00/news/ct-xpm-2002-03-15-0203150197-story.html |archive-date=September 28, 2018 |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> They had [[bulletproof vest]]s, [[walkie-talkie]]s, guns and badges, but Rich didn't believe them and ran.<ref name=\"Loven1999\"/><ref name=\"Madhani2002\"/> Foster and Prince chased and shot Rich, then stole several hundred dollars and keys from his pockets.<ref name=\"Madhani2002\"/> He died in hospital four days later from extensive blood loss.<ref name=\"WilsonMadhani1999\">{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Terry |last2=Madhani |first2=Aamer |date=October 24, 1999 |title=Rush\u2019s Son Dies; Police Question Man in Shooting |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1999-10-24-9910240232-story.html |dead-url=no |work=Chicago Tribune |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928070930/https://www.chicagotribune.com/g00/news/ct-xpm-1999-10-24-9910240232-story.html |archive-date=September 28, 2018 |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> Foster told police that he and Prince were coming to collect $110,000 worth of cocaine that Rich had been paid to procure but hadn't delivered.<ref name=\"McCormick1999\"/><ref name=\"Madhani2002\"/>  Rich's friends didn't believe Foster's story, with some suggesting it may have been a case of mistaken identity.<ref name=\"McCormick1999\"/> Rush said Rich \"was involved in positive\u2014as far as I know\u2014endeavors\", adding \"as parents, we don't always know\".<ref name=\"McCormick1999\"/> Foster was sentenced to 60 years in prison for Rich's murder, and Prince was sentenced to 50 years.<ref name=\"NWI2002\">{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |date=July 27, 2002 |title=Man Convicted of Killing Rush\u2019s Son Sentenced |url=https://www.nwitimes.com/uncategorized/man-convicted-of-killing-rush-s-son-sentenced/article_b5e32a7e-ad9a-58fb-8521-f482f725e4d2.html |dead-url=no |work=[[The Times of Northwest Indiana|The Times of Northwest Indiana (NWI)]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928081840/https://www.nwitimes.com/uncategorized/man-convicted-of-killing-rush-s-son-sentenced/article_b5e32a7e-ad9a-58fb-8521-f482f725e4d2.html |archive-date=September 28, 2018 |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> The murder prompted Rush to prioritize efforts to reduce gun violence.<ref name=\"Loven1999\"/>\n\nIn 2008, Rush had a rare type of malignant tumor removed from his [[salivary gland]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abclocal.go.com/wls/story?section=news/local&id=6306057|title=Chicago News|publisher=Abclocal.go.com|date=August 4, 2008 |accessdate=August 23, 2010}}</ref> Rush is a member of [[Iota Phi Theta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iotaphitheta.org/about/notable-iota-men-2|title=Notable Iota Men|publisher=[[Iota Phi Theta]]|accessdate=August 23, 2010|deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213051221/http://www.iotaphitheta.org/about/notable-iota-men-2|archivedate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> According to a DNA analysis conducted under the auspices of the TV program, ''Know Your Heritage,'' he is descended mainly from the [[Ashanti people]] of [[Ghana]].<ref name=\"africa\">{{YouTube|SYxSOI6resY|\"Bobby Rush Ancestry Reveal\", ''Know Your Ancestry'', February 6, 2012, The Africa Channel}}</ref> Rush attributed his election to congress to [[Tony Robbins]].<ref name=\"McRobertsCohen1999\"/> His heroes include [[Abraham Lincoln]], [[Kit Carson]] and Huey P. Newton.<ref name=\"McRobertsCohen1999\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*[[List of African-American United States Representatives]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.house.gov/rush/ Congressman Bobby Rush] official U.S. House website\n*{{DMOZ|Regional/North_America/United_States/Illinois/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Bobby_Rush_%5BD-1%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=R000515 | votesmart=26831 | fec=H2IL01042 | congress=bobby-rush/R000515 }}\n*{{C-SPAN|Bobby Rush}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Charles Hayes (politician)|Charles Hayes]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Illinois|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Illinois's 1st congressional district]]|years=1993\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ed Royce]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=43rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bobby Scott (politician)|Bobby Scott]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{IL-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurren